We have now created another model with dev ratio of 0.6277431 and MSE = 282.0387481. The model features are not quite so stunning, but it is simpler, easier to interpret, and incorporates more data. Well find that this model doesnt put brca at the top. In fact, its almost completely shrunken from the model entirely. There could be a lot of reasons for this, but one might be that the 5 year survival rate for breast cancer is nearly 90%. This could be attributable to treatment regimens, but other cancers may be easier to predict death rate.

Using a test su ggested by Tshibir ani in his text , (statistical learni ng with sparsity, t he lasso and its generalizat ions, p.161), we find that the lung-bronchial cancer incidence rate, the raw incidence rate for all cancers, and both college education and high school education status have a nonzero coefficient in the least angle regression model. The text suggests that this test is superior to the covariance test in that the entire model is not tested at each knot, but rather whether the partial correlation of the given predictor entered in that step [knot] is zero, adjusting for other variables currently in the model (p.161). As such, it does not simply test for the lasso path, but for the individual contribution of each predictor to the model. As we might gather, this agrees completely with the covariance test results and with the confidence intervals that do not contain zero in the least angle regression estimate confidence interval. It is often said that p-values are not sharp cutoffs and the adjustment procedure here has been very conservative.

Percent public coverage alone, relationship to death rate and incidence rate: Its compelling that the relationship between poverty and death rate is strongest in certain regions, namely in the west. A more indepth view of states within the west state areas this may provide additional insight. Well add back in the state and county data to see which states/counties may be responsible for the incredibly weak link between poverty and death rate in the west. Ternary plots are uncommon, but a powerful way to display complex relationships of three independent variables (http://science.sciencemag.org/content/sci/215/4537/1191.full.pdf). Figure 4. Ternary plot suggests that the 3-way relationship between education, poverty, insurance coverage differs as the polygon placement and shape differs, suggesting that numerical relationships between these three variabes is not equally strong in all pairwise relationships. Notably, we also find a large central peak in the south plot that shows that each of all three variables are related to each other (percentages of poverty, of indiviudals without a bachelors degree, and percentile death rate). The high amount brightly colored points suggests counties with a high percentage of indiviudals with only public coverage. In short, all of the variables are related well in the south, but not so in the west (which contains lower income areas that are highly educated and with the lowest cancer areas in the country).

spacingTest<-function(X,Y)
{lar_full<-selectiveInference::lar(x = X,y = Y)
spacing_test<-selectiveInference::larInf(lar_full) #this is a better test that actually gives inference of the individual predictor's correlation.
spacing_test$predictor <- colnames(X)[spacing_test$var]
#class(spacing_test_table)<-"list"
ci_tibble <- spacing_test$ci %>% as.tibble()
colnames(ci_tibble)<-c("lower_CI","upper_CI")
covtest_spacing_pval <- tibble(predictor = colnames(X)[spacing_test$vars],spacing.p.value = spacing_test$pv.spacing, covtest.pval = spacing_test$pv.covtest) %>%
  bind_cols(ci_tibble) %>% 
  mutate(ci_midpoint = (upper_CI+lower_CI)/2) %>% 
  mutate(significance = ifelse(spacing.p.value < 0.05, "*","")) %>% 
  mutate(adj.spacing.pvalue = p.adjust(spacing.p.value)) %>% 
  mutate(significance_adj = ifelse(adj.spacing.pvalue < 0.05, "*","")) %>%
  select(covtest.pval,spacing.p.value,significance,adj.spacing.pvalue,significance_adj,everything()) %>% 
  dplyr::arrange(spacing.p.value)
}#nrow(X)

The spacing tes t is even more str ingent way to d etermine what variabl es are most importa nt in the model than simply performing las so and provid es p-values. From this, well find that indeed married households play a role in reducing cancer death rate, at least in the west. We can say that the coefficient in the model is nonzero and the sign is negative, indicating an inverse relationship, in line with raw pearson correlation of \(R=\)-0.2823533 between these variables in the western united states. An article published last year in SSM population health suggests several reasons for this (higher earning or higher education spouses tend to be beneficial for survival rates, https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ssmph.2016.12.007). The article is right in line with our model, which puts education as a highly important variable.

Whats rather a mazing here is tha t the proportio n of deviance explain ed by this model ex plains a whopping % of the variance. The model looks reasonable, with the exception of two outliers. The target death rate there is roughly 3 times the national average, the poverty percent is above average, median income is below, and the percent of individuals with a college education hits the single digits. This is an outlier in the sense that it is a point that is apart from the rest in a res vs fitted plot, but it is a real feature of the data and should not be removed. Upon looking for evidence of htis, a recent article in JAMA cited this information (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28118455), specifically mentioning this county last year. The article also mentions Utah and Idaho as low regions, just as we found.

ecig_rate <- read_csv("./smoking/Behavioral_Risk_Factor_Data__Tobacco_Use__2011_to_present_.csv") %>%
  janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  filter(year == "2017" & topic_desc == "E-Cigarette Use (Adults)" & race == "All Races" & response == "Never" & gender == "Overall") %>% 
  mutate(pct_have_smoked = 1-data_value) %>% 
  mutate(pct_never_smoker = data_value) %>%
  select(location_desc,data_value,pct_have_smoked,pct_never_smoker,location_abbr) %>% 
  arrange(-pct_have_smoked)
